Introduction

The United Nations (UN) is an intergovernmental organization founded in 1946 to promote international cooperation. It now represents 193 member states. The General Assembly is the largest body, with a seat for every member of the UN. It discusses topics of international importance such as maintaining peace and security, providing humanitarian aid, and protecting human rights.

We will be analyzing a dataset containing the full history of General Assembly votes by each country to determine what countries vote similarly and which do not. We will also explore how this changes through time.

In this problem, we will combine information from three sources to create the datasets that we will use to study voting behavior.

Compute the percentage in which the US and Canada voted the same. Calculate this percentage for each year and call it agreement. Fit a linear model using lm() to predict agreement with year.

# Removing years with NA
datx <-y %>% 
    filter(!is.na(year)) %>%
    group_by(year) %>% 
    summarize(agreement=mean(USA==Canada,na.rm=TRUE)*100)

# Basic linear regression
m <- datx %>% lm(agreement ~ year,data=.)


summary(m)

Problem 2B

In the previous problem we found a negative trend in the agreement between the USA and Canada throughout the years. Interpreting this linear model would imply that disagreement between these two counties was worse during the Clinton administration (1992-2000) than the Reagan administration (1980-1998).

Now, instead of blindly interpreting the regression results, plot the data and use a smoother to estimate a trend. Based on this analysis, how do thes Regan and Clinton administrations compare?

Hint: Make sure to pick a window size or span that creates a trend that goes through data.

library(broom)
#I feel a span of between .2 and .25 creates the best fit
span <-.2

mod <- loess(agreement~year, degree=1, span = span, data=datx)
loess_fit <- augment(mod)


# Plotting the loess fit and highlighting the data corresponding to Reagan and Clinton administrations
datx %>% ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(year, agreement)) + 
  geom_line(aes(x=year, y=.fitted), data=loess_fit, color="red") +
  annotate("rect", xmin=1992, xmax=2000, ymin=-Inf, ymax=Inf, alpha=.2, fill="blue") +
  annotate("rect", xmin=1980, xmax=1989, ymin=-Inf, ymax=Inf, alpha=.2, fill="green") +
  annotate("text", x=1996,y=100,label="Clinton") +
  annotate("text", x=1984,y=100,label="Reagan") +
  ylab("Agreement % (USA and Canada)") +
  ggtitle("UN Voting agreement between USA and Canada")

# We can see quite clearly here that during the Reagan administration, the voting agreement between the USA and Canada worsened significantly. The Clinton administration saw an overall improvement, but it was comparitively small change.

# In numbers, we see a decline of ~39% during the Reagan administration and a ~7% increase during the Clinton administration
datx%>% filter(year %in% c(1980,1989,1992,2000)) %>% mutate(administration=ifelse(year>1990,"Clinton","Reagan")) %>% group_by(administration) %>% summarise(change=last(agreement)-first(agreement))

Make the plot above for the agreement through time between the US and the following countries: Israel, UK, Mexico, Cuba, and China. Make two plots: one for important votes to non-important votes.

plotVotes <- function(important=TRUE){

Describe the observed patterns.

Your answer here: On important issues, the US voting agreement with Israel is very strong. In many years, the US and Israel agree on every vote. In contrast, the US and Cuba disagree strongly. The disagreement with China is less strong, but every year, there is at most a 50% agreement record. Problem 3C

We see that obtain a very high accuracy, but note that this is a random variable due to the random split of our data. Try 10 new random splits and report on how much our accuracy changes.

# Placing previous code into a function

runtestGLM <- function(indata=usa.non.null.votes) {
  inTrain <- createDataPartition(y = indata$y,
                               p=0.8)
  train_set <- slice(indata, inTrain$Resample1)
  test_set <- slice(indata, -inTrain$Resample1)

  # Fitting the GLM based only on the countries voting patterns
  glm_fit <- glm(y~.,data=train_set)


  f_hat <- round(predict(glm_fit, newdata = test_set, 
                 type = "response"))

   tab <- table(pred=f_hat, truth=test_set$y)

   return(confusionMatrix(tab)$overall["Accuracy"])
}

set.seed(1)
# Re-running 10 times
accuracy <- replicate(10,runtestGLM())

# Checking spread of results
summary(accuracy)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.8615  0.9385  0.9538  0.9446  0.9692  0.9846
sd(accuracy)/sqrt(length(accuracy))
## [1] 0.01151279

Problem 3D

Compare your glm() model to a knn(). Use the train() function to run 10 cross validations with leaving out 80% of the data. Plot your results.

runtestKNN <- function(indata=usa.non.null.votes) {
  inTrain <- createDataPartition(y = indata$y,
                               p=0.8)
  train_set <- slice(indata, inTrain$Resample1)
  test_set <- slice(indata, -inTrain$Resample1)
  knn_fit <- knn3(y~.,data = train_set)
  f_hat <- round(predict(knn_fit, newdata = test_set)[,2])
  
  tab <- table(pred=f_hat, truth=test_set$y)
  return(confusionMatrix(tab)$overall["Accuracy"])
}


set.seed(1)
# Re-running 10 times using default of k=5
accuracy <- replicate(10,runtestKNN())

# Checking spread of results
summary(accuracy)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9077  0.9269  0.9538  0.9446  0.9654  0.9692
sd(accuracy)/sqrt(length(accuracy))
## [1] 0.007675195
# Over the same training data we see a better accuracy than we observed in the glm. Even though our mean score matched what was observed in GLM, our se is much smaller at .007
